import folium
import requests
import pandas

arrest_table = pandas.read_csv("https://cmsc320.github.io/files/BPD_Arrests.csv")

arrest_table = arrest_table[pandas.notnull(arrest_table["Location 1"])]

arrest_table["lat"], arrest_table["long"] = arrest_table["Location 1"].str.split(",").str
arrest_table["lat"] = arrest_table["lat"].str.replace("(", "").astype(float)
arrest_table["long"] = arrest_table["long"].str.replace(")", "").astype(float)

# Differentiate between male and female minors, age under 18 years old

map_age =  folium.Map(location=[39.29, -76.61], zoom_start=11)
table = arrest_table[arrest_table['age'] < 18]

for (index, row) in table.iterrows():
    if (row['sex'] == 'M'):
        folium.Marker(
            location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']],
            popup= 'Age: ' + str(row.loc['age']) + ' Race: '+  row.loc['race'] + 
                 ' Arrested on: ' + str(row.loc['arrestDate']) + ' at: ' + str(row.loc['arrestTime'])
                 + ' Offense: ' + row.loc['incidentOffense'], icon = folium.Icon(color='blue', icon='warning')).add_to(map_age)
        
    elif (row['sex']== 'F'):
        folium.Marker(
            location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']],
            popup='Age: ' + str(row.loc['age']) + 'Race: ' +  row.loc['race'] + 
                 'Arrested on: ' + str(row.loc['arrestDate']) + 'at: ' + str(row.loc['arrestTime'])
                 + "Offense: " + row.loc['incidentOffense'], icon = folium.Icon(color='pink', icon='warning')).add_to(map_age)
map_age

In this map, I used markers to indicate male and female arrests throughout Baltimore that are minors, meaning they are under 18 years of age. The blue markers indicate a male arrest and a pink marker indicates a female arrest. These results are not filtered by district. This map shows all crimes committed by minors that are provided in the arrest_table. The markers are not concentrated to a specific district, rather they are spread out across Baltimore. This map shows that majority of the arrests in Baltimore were male suspects. If we assume that other age groups follow this trend, we can predict that across all the age groups, there will be more crimes committed by males than females. This correlation does not imply causation, and there may still be an increase in crimes committed by females, but according to this map, we can see that there are significantly more male arrests than female.

# Differentiate between race, females in the Northern District

map_race =  folium.Map(location=[39.29, -76.61], zoom_start=11)

table = arrest_table[arrest_table['sex'] == "F"]
table = table[table['district'] == "NORTHERN"]

for (index, row) in table.iterrows():
    if (row['race'] == 'A'): # Asian
        folium.Marker(
            location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']],
            popup= 'Age: ' + str(row.loc['age']) + ' Race: '+  row.loc['race'] + 
                 ' Arrested on: ' + str(row.loc['arrestDate']) + ' at: ' + str(row.loc['arrestTime'])
                 + ' Offense: ' + row.loc['incidentOffense'], icon = folium.Icon(color='red', icon='warning')).add_to(map_race)
        
    elif (row['race'] == 'B'): # Black
        folium.Marker(
            location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']],
            popup= 'Age: ' + str(row.loc['age']) + ' Race: '+  row.loc['race'] + 
                 ' Arrested on: ' + str(row.loc['arrestDate']) + ' at: ' + str(row.loc['arrestTime'])
                 + ' Offense: ' + row.loc['incidentOffense'], icon = folium.Icon(color='orange', icon='warning')).add_to(map_race)
        
    elif (row['race'] == 'H'): # Hispanic
        folium.Marker(
            location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']],
            popup= 'Age: ' + str(row.loc['age']) + ' Race: '+  row.loc['race'] + 
                 ' Arrested on: ' + str(row.loc['arrestDate']) + ' at: ' + str(row.loc['arrestTime'])
                 + ' Offense: ' + row.loc['incidentOffense'], icon = folium.Icon(color='yellow', icon='warning')).add_to(map_race)
        
    elif (row['race'] == 'I'): # Indian/Native American??
        folium.Marker(
            location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']],
            popup= 'Age: ' + str(row.loc['age']) + ' Race: '+  row.loc['race'] +

    elif (row['race'] == 'U'): # Unidentified
        folium.Marker(
            location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']],
            popup= 'Age: ' + str(row.loc['age']) + ' Race: '+  row.loc['race'] + 
                 ' Arrested on: ' + str(row.loc['arrestDate']) + ' at: ' + str(row.loc['arrestTime'])
                 + ' Offense: ' + row.loc['incidentOffense'], icon = folium.Icon(color='blue', icon='warning')).add_to(map_race)
        
    elif (row['race'] == 'W'): # White
        folium.Marker(
            location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']],
            popup= 'Age: ' + str(row.loc['age']) + ' Race: '+  row.loc['race'] + 
                 ' Arrested on: ' + str(row.loc['arrestDate']) + ' at: ' + str(row.loc['arrestTime'])
                 + ' Offense: ' + row.loc['incidentOffense'], icon = folium.Icon(color='purple', icon='warning')).add_to(map_race)

In this map, I used markers to show different races of female arrests in the Northern District. Red markers indicate Asian, orange indicates Black, yellow indicates Hispanic, green indicates Indian/Native American, blue indicates Unidentified, and purple indicates White. In the Northern district, the top two races that committed majority of the crimes are White and Black. There are more crimes committed by black females than white females, however both groups exceed the number of crimes committed by any other race. If this trend continues in other districts of Baltimore, we can predict that both white and black races will dominate other races with the most crimes committed.

# Differentiate between crimes committed by senior citizens over 65 years of age

map_crime =  folium.Map(location=[39.29, -76.61], zoom_start=11)

table = arrest_table[arrest_table['age'] >= 65]
table1 = table[table['chargeDescription'].str.contains('asslt| Assault', na=False)]
table2 = table[table['chargeDescription'].str.contains('Burglary|Theft|theft', na=False)]
table3 = table[table['chargeDescription'].str.contains('Possess', na=False)]


for (index, row) in table1.iterrows():
    folium.CircleMarker(radius = 5, location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']], color='red').add_to(map_crime)
    
for (index, row) in table2.iterrows():
    folium.CircleMarker(radius = 5, location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']], color='blue').add_to(map_crime)
    
for (index, row) in table3.iterrows():
    folium.CircleMarker(radius = 5, location = [row.loc['lat'], row['long']], color='green').add_to(map_crime)
    
map_crime

In this map, I wanted to show specific crimes committed by senior citizens throughout Baltimore. I chose possession, Burglary/theft and assault. The possession charge seems to be the most common out of the 3 crimes and is mostly around Central Baltimore more than any other area. Central Baltimore has a very dense population so it makes sense to have most of the crimes taking place in this district. I used circle markers to show a crime within a radius of 5 so the crimes in Central Baltimore may be more clustered than in the map. I chose these three crimes because they are very distinct from one another and have a low chance of overlap. For example, some burglaries may include a firearm so it wouldn't make sense to compre burglaries and firearm charges. Since these are senior citizens, it would make more sense to have a crime that is less physical due to their age. This correlation does not imply causation, but it shows a trend that a possession charge is more common amongst senior citizens in Baltimore
